HOW OUGHT WE REGARD THE GIBEONITE COVENANT?

The first phase of the book, narrated in chapters 1–12, displays a clear progres-
sion. Progress naturally continues in the second part of the book, but the nature 
of the activity is now distributed throughout Israel rather than being enacted by 
the people of Israel as a whole, as has been the case up to this point. This more 
fragmented activity allows also for a different kind of arrangement of the material. 
The chunks constituting the settlement account can be readily seen: chapter 13 
provides a reprise of the Transjordanian settlement; chapters 14–17 describe the 
settlement of Judah, Ephraim, and the remaining half-tribe of Manasseh (the latter 
two being the "Joseph" tribes; cf. 16:1, 4) arranged from Gilgal, the original Israelite 
camp west of the Jordan; chapters 18–19 account for the remainder of the tribal 
settlements managed from Shiloh; while chapters 20–21 complete the distribution 
with the civic allotments for refuge (ch. 20) and the tribe of Levi (ch. 21), which does
